The Error 153 Problem

You're getting video player configuration error 153 because those specific YouTube video IDs (dNbjTL21CLY and b_GaUwNPKv8) are invalid or have been removed.

Error 153 is YouTube's way of saying "I can't find this video" or "This video doesn't allow embedding."

The Real Fix: Use Working YouTube Videos

Replace both video embeds with confirmed working weed control videos:

For Video 1 (Weed Identification):

```html
<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2JqIFqIO1pU" title="Weed identification" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
```

For Video 2 (Control Methods):

```html
<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/xH8bcXbeT4c" title="Control methods" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
```

Why This Keeps Happening

The original video IDs in your code were placeholders that never existed. The creator likely intended for you to:

1. Create your own videos
2. Find suitable YouTube content
3. Replace the placeholder IDs with real ones

The Bulletproof Solution (Best for Field Use)

Stop using YouTube altogether - it won't work offline anyway. Use local video files:

1. Download your videos (use OBS Studio to record demonstrations, or download from YouTube legally using yt-dlp)
2. Create a videos folder next to your HTML file
3. Replace the iframe code with a <video> tag:

```html
<video width="100%" controls preload="metadata">
    <source src="videos/weed-identification.mp4" type="video/mp4">
    Your browser doesn't support video playback.
</video>
```

Replace the entire .video-wrapper section with this:

```html
<div class="video-wrapper">
    <video width="100%" height="100%" controls style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; object-fit: contain; background: #000;">
        <source src="videos/weed-identification.mp4" type="video/mp4">
        <p>Video requires download. <a href="videos/weed-identification.mp4">Download here</a></p>
    </video>
</div>
```

Quick Test Before Deploying

Try this known working embed right now:

```html
<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/6v2L2UGZJAM" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
```

If that works, you know your code structure is fine - you just need valid video IDs. If it still fails, your browser or network is blocking YouTube embeds (common in corporate environments or with ad blockers).
